{
  "V1": {
    "authors": [
      "James Nevison"
    ],
    "body": {
      "summary": [
        "Rosé wine is great, but there’s also been an influx of fun, rosé-adjacent potables lately"
      ],
      "sections": [
        {
          "headline": [],
          "paragraphs": [
            "I’m certainly seeing the world through more pink-coloured glasses these days. Or, more specifically, through rosé-filled wine glasses. Regardless, the effect is the same: There’s just something cheery about sipping a glass of rosé as the sun shines. And while straight-up rosé is making more appearances, there’s also been an influx of fun, rosé-adjacent potables lately. Spoiler alert: They’re proving just as enjoyable."
          ]
        },
        {
          "headline": [
            "La Vieille Ferme 2025 Rosé, France ($14.99, #559393)"
          ],
          "paragraphs": [
            "The reality is that the pink wine category itself offers up a myriad of shades. Sure, some rosés are bright pink, but others — like this perennial stalwart — pour more onion skin in colour. La Vieille Ferme is a widely available, crowd pleasing bottle of rosé. A blend of Cinsault, Grenache and Syrah, it’s quite aromatic and offers berry, citrus, and herbal notes before a bright, tart entry. Acidity is evident throughout, with a fresh and almost savoury, herby finish. It’s not complicated but it is refreshing and fun, not to mention a great pairing partner for a backyard cookout or weekend picnic.",
            "Bottom line: B. Friendly, versatile rosé."
          ]
        },
        {
          "headline": [
            "No Compromise 2024 Carricante, Italy ($19.99, #192961)"
          ],
          "paragraphs": [
            "All right, “orange wine” is not rosé. But there is kinship, as orange wine is essentially the inverse of pink wine. When making traditional rosé, winemakers give red grapes minimal skin contact with the wine (leading to a pink colour). When making orange wine, winemakers leave white grapes in skin contact with the wine (leading to an orange colour). When done well, the end result for both is refreshing and engaging. This is on display with No Compromise, a tea leaf, potpourri and citrus-imbued orange wine made from organically-grown Carricante grapes in Sicily. Savoury vibes build on a dry, lip-smacking finish.",
            "Bottom line: B+. Orange is the new pink."
          ]
        },
        {
          "headline": [
            "Dillon’s Small Batch Distillers Signature Cocktails Variety Pack, B.C. ($21.99, #683213)"
          ],
          "paragraphs": [
            "Finally, something a little different. Full disclosure, I haven’t been the biggest cheerleader of ready-to-drink, or RTD, beverages. After all, how difficult is it to make your own Cosmopolitan or Espresso Martini from scratch? But as the weather warms and outdoor adventures beckon, the convenience factor does really kick in. Cue Dillon’s Signature Cocktail Variety Pack, which offers two 222mL cans each of premade Raspberry & Ginger Vodka Mule, Cold Brew Espresso Martini, and White Cranberry Cosmopolitan. The latter pours a still, cotton candy pink and certainly delivers on the promised Cosmo with evident cranberry notes and a luxurious, orange liqueur kick.",
            "Bottom line: B. Follow the instructions: “Simply pour & garnish.”"
          ]
        },
        {
          "headline": [
            "The Swirl: Best of the Bench"
          ],
          "paragraphs": [
            "The Naramata Bench Wineries Association is again presenting their “Best of the Bench.” This year’s event takes place from 6-9 p.m. on June 11 at Bench 1775 Winery (1775 Naramata Rd., Penticton). The event will offer up the 12 wines declared this year’s “Best of the Bench,” alongside a diverse selection of bottles from more than 25 Naramata Bench wineries — all favoured while mingling with winemakers and winery owners and enjoying tapas and canapés. Tickets to this 19+ event start at $99 and are available at naramatabench.com."
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
